Note:
DEQUE - Double-Ended Queue (Block-Linked) Tier 0 Primitive

This file implements a deque as a doubly-linked list of fixed-size array
blocks. Each block holds DEQUE_BLOCK_CAPACITY slots; the block list grows
at either end with O(1) amortized cost.

Architecture:
- Doubly-linked chain of blocks. Each block has:
    offset 0:  prev block pointer (8 bytes)
    offset 8:  next block pointer (8 bytes)
    offset 16: head index inside block (8 bytes) - first occupied slot
    offset 24: tail index inside block (8 bytes) - one past last occupied
    offset 32+: slot array of DEQUE_BLOCK_CAPACITY * 8 bytes
- Block size = 32 + DEQUE_BLOCK_CAPACITY * 8 bytes
- Deque header (48 bytes):
    offset 0:  head block pointer (8 bytes)
    offset 8:  tail block pointer (8 bytes)
    offset 16: size (total element count, 8 bytes)
    offset 24: head_block index (first occupied slot in head block, 8 bytes)
    offset 32: tail_block index (one past last occupied slot in tail block, 8 bytes)
    offset 40: block_capacity (slots per block, 8 bytes)

Behavior:
- push_front: write into head_block at index (head_block_index - 1).
  If head_block_index is 0, allocate a new block at the front and write
  at index (block_capacity - 1).
- push_back: write into tail_block at tail_block_index, then advance.
  If tail_block_index hits block_capacity, allocate a new block at back.
- pop_front / pop_back symmetric, freeing now-empty blocks.

Use cases:
- BFS/DFS frontiers with both push_front (priority urgent) and push_back
- Sliding-window algorithms
- Work-stealing queue backing
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

Let DEQUE_BLOCK_CAPACITY be 64
Let DEQUE_ELEMENT_SIZE be 8
Let DEQUE_BLOCK_HEADER_SIZE be 32
Let DEQUE_HEADER_SIZE be 48
Let DEQUE_BLOCK_PREV_OFFSET be 0
Let DEQUE_BLOCK_NEXT_OFFSET be 8
Let DEQUE_BLOCK_HEAD_OFFSET be 16
Let DEQUE_BLOCK_TAIL_OFFSET be 24

Note: ============================================================================
Note: INTERNAL HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Allocate a single deque block. New blocks have prev/next set to 0 and
head == tail at the block midpoint so subsequent push_front or push_back
both have room without requiring an immediate second allocation. Choosing
the midpoint reduces the chance that a mixed-direction workload thrashes
the block boundary.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Block size = 32 + 64 * 8 = 544 bytes. Midpoint index = block_capacity / 2.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(BLOCK_CAPACITY) bytes per block.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Internal helper; caller controls insertion into the linked structure.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_alloc_block" returns Integer:
    Let block_size be DEQUE_BLOCK_HEADER_SIZE plus (DEQUE_BLOCK_CAPACITY multiplied by DEQUE_ELEMENT_SIZE)
    Let block be proc allocate from Layout with block_size
    If block is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mid be DEQUE_BLOCK_CAPACITY divided by 2
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with block, DEQUE_BLOCK_PREV_OFFSET, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with block, DEQUE_BLOCK_NEXT_OFFSET, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with block, DEQUE_BLOCK_HEAD_OFFSET, mid
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with block, DEQUE_BLOCK_TAIL_OFFSET, mid
    Return block
End Process

@Reasoning
Compute the byte address of slot 'index' within a block. Centralized to
keep the slot layout (header + slot_index * 8) in one place.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Address = block + DEQUE_BLOCK_HEADER_SIZE + index * DEQUE_ELEMENT_SIZE.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Trivially inlined.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-validated index; no internal bounds check.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_block_slot_addr" takes block as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    Return block plus (DEQUE_BLOCK_HEADER_SIZE plus (index multiplied by DEQUE_ELEMENT_SIZE))
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTION / DESTRUCTION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Create an empty deque with exactly one block pre-allocated. Pre-allocation
removes the null-check from the hot push path; the small fixed cost is
acceptable for the much-simpler invariants in push/pop.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocate 48 bytes for the deque header, allocate the first block, wire
head_block == tail_block == that block, size = 0, and inherit the block's
midpoint indices.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: header (48 bytes) + first block (544 bytes) = 592 bytes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
On allocation failure either step returns 0 and frees any partial state.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_create" returns Integer:
    Let dq be proc allocate from Layout with DEQUE_HEADER_SIZE
    If dq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let block be proc deque_alloc_block
    If block is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with dq
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mid be DEQUE_BLOCK_CAPACITY divided by 2
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 0, block
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 8, block
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 16, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 24, mid
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 32, mid
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 40, DEQUE_BLOCK_CAPACITY
    Return dq
End Process

@Reasoning
Walk the block chain freeing each block, then free the deque header.
Slot contents are opaque words; we do not free them because the deque
does not own them.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Start at head_block, save next, free current, advance. Terminate when
next == 0. Then free header.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(B) in number of blocks. Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller must own the deque. Slot pointees are not freed.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_destroy" takes dq as Integer returns Integer:
    If dq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let cur be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 0
    While cur is not equal to 0:
        Let next be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with cur, DEQUE_BLOCK_NEXT_OFFSET
        proc deallocate from Layout with cur
        Set cur to next
    End While
    proc deallocate from Layout with dq
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SIZE / EMPTY QUERIES
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns the total element count. Stored as a field so this is O(1)
without walking blocks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Read 8-byte size field at offset 16.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_size" takes dq as Integer returns Integer:
    If dq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 16
End Process

@Reasoning
Convenience predicate for empty deque.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Returns 1 if size == 0, otherwise 0.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_is_empty" takes dq as Integer returns Integer:
    If dq is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let sz be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 16
    If sz is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PUSH OPERATIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Push value at the back. If the tail block has room (tail_block_index <
block_capacity) we write into it. Otherwise we allocate a new block,
link it after the current tail, and write at index 0.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Read tail_block, tail_block_index.
2) If index == block_capacity, allocate new block; link prev/next; new
   block's head = 0, tail = 0; update deque.tail = new block; reset
   tail_block_index = 0.
3) Write value at slot address; increment tail_block_index in both the
   block header and the deque header; increment size.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: amortized O(1) - allocation only when block boundary hit.
Space: O(1) per push, plus one new block per BLOCK_CAPACITY pushes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on allocation failure. Internal state remains consistent on
failure: the new block is freed before the deque is observed.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_push_back" takes dq as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    If dq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let tail_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 8
    Let tail_idx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 32
    Let cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 40
    If tail_idx is greater than or equal to cap:
        Let new_block be proc deque_alloc_block
        If new_block is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Note: head and tail in new block start at 0 for a fresh back-block
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_HEAD_OFFSET, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_TAIL_OFFSET, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_PREV_OFFSET, tail_block
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tail_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_NEXT_OFFSET, new_block
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 8, new_block
        Set tail_block to new_block
        Set tail_idx to 0
    End If
    Let addr be proc deque_block_slot_addr with tail_block, tail_idx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with addr, 0, value
    Set tail_idx to tail_idx plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tail_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_TAIL_OFFSET, tail_idx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 32, tail_idx
    Let sz be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 16, sz plus 1
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Push at the front. If head_block_index is 0 we cannot decrement so we
allocate a new block before the current head and write at index
(block_capacity - 1).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Read head_block, head_block_index.
2) If index == 0, allocate new block; link prev/next; set new block's
   head = block_capacity - 1, tail = block_capacity (full at far end);
   update deque.head = new block; head_block_index = block_capacity.
3) Decrement head_block_index, write value at slot, update block.head
   and deque.head_block_index; increment size.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: amortized O(1). Space: O(1) per push plus one new block per
BLOCK_CAPACITY front-pushes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Allocation failure returns 0 and leaves the deque unchanged.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_push_front" takes dq as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    If dq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let head_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 0
    Let head_idx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 24
    Let cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 40
    If head_idx is equal to 0:
        Let new_block be proc deque_alloc_block
        If new_block is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
        Note: A fresh front-block has head and tail both at cap; we will
        Note: decrement head below and write at index (cap - 1).
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_HEAD_OFFSET, cap
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_TAIL_OFFSET, cap
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_NEXT_OFFSET, head_block
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with head_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_PREV_OFFSET, new_block
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 0, new_block
        Set head_block to new_block
        Set head_idx to cap
    End If
    Set head_idx to head_idx minus 1
    Let addr be proc deque_block_slot_addr with head_block, head_idx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with addr, 0, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with head_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_HEAD_OFFSET, head_idx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 24, head_idx
    Let sz be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 16, sz plus 1
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: POP OPERATIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Pop the front element. If after the pop the head block becomes empty
and there is a successor block, we free the head block and advance.
This bounds memory at O(size + BLOCK_CAPACITY) and avoids unbounded
empty-block accumulation under alternating push/pop workloads.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Empty check via size == 0.
2) Read head_block, head_block_index. The element is at slot[head_idx].
3) Advance head_block_index, decrement size, update block.head.
4) If head_block becomes empty (head == tail) and a next block exists,
   unlink head and free the old block; restore head_block_index from
   the new head block's head field.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: amortized O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on empty deque; caller must check deque_is_empty first if
0 is a legitimate slot value.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_pop_front" takes dq as Integer returns Integer:
    If dq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sz be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 16
    If sz is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let head_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 0
    Let head_idx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 24
    Let addr be proc deque_block_slot_addr with head_block, head_idx
    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
    Set head_idx to head_idx plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with head_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_HEAD_OFFSET, head_idx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 24, head_idx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 16, sz minus 1
    Let blk_tail be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with head_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_TAIL_OFFSET
    Let next_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with head_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_NEXT_OFFSET
    If head_idx is greater than or equal to blk_tail:
        If next_block is not equal to 0:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with next_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_PREV_OFFSET, 0
            proc deallocate from Layout with head_block
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 0, next_block
            Let new_head_idx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with next_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_HEAD_OFFSET
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 24, new_head_idx
        End If
    End If
    Return value
End Process

@Reasoning
Pop the back element. Mirror of pop_front with the tail-block free path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1) Empty check.
2) Read tail_block, tail_block_index. Element is at slot[tail_idx - 1].
3) Decrement tail_block_index, decrement size.
4) If the tail block becomes empty (head == tail) and a prev block exists,
   free the tail block and update deque.tail to prev, restoring
   tail_block_index from the prev block's tail field.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: amortized O(1). Space: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns 0 on empty deque.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_pop_back" takes dq as Integer returns Integer:
    If dq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sz be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 16
    If sz is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let tail_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 8
    Let tail_idx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 32
    Set tail_idx to tail_idx minus 1
    Let addr be proc deque_block_slot_addr with tail_block, tail_idx
    Let value be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tail_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_TAIL_OFFSET, tail_idx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 32, tail_idx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 16, sz minus 1
    Let blk_head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tail_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_HEAD_OFFSET
    Let prev_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tail_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_PREV_OFFSET
    If tail_idx is less than or equal to blk_head:
        If prev_block is not equal to 0:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with prev_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_NEXT_OFFSET, 0
            proc deallocate from Layout with tail_block
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 8, prev_block
            Let new_tail_idx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with prev_block, DEQUE_BLOCK_TAIL_OFFSET
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, 32, new_tail_idx
        End If
    End If
    Return value
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PEEK OPERATIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Read the front element without removing it. Exists so callers do not
have to pop-then-push to inspect.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
If size == 0 return 0. Otherwise read slot[head_block_index] in
head_block.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Empty returns 0.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_peek_front" takes dq as Integer returns Integer:
    If dq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sz be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 16
    If sz is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let head_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 0
    Let head_idx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 24
    Let addr be proc deque_block_slot_addr with head_block, head_idx
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Read the back element. The tail index is "one past the last", so the
last element is at slot[tail_idx - 1].
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
If empty return 0. Otherwise read slot[tail_block_index - 1] of
tail_block.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Empty returns 0.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_peek_back" takes dq as Integer returns Integer:
    If dq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let sz be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 16
    If sz is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let tail_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 8
    Let tail_idx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, 32
    Let addr be proc deque_block_slot_addr with tail_block, tail_idx minus 1
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with addr, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: COMPATIBILITY API - mirrors queue (push_back/pop_front/peek_front)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Aliases that let a deque be used wherever a queue is expected, so
callers can substitute a deque without changing call sites.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each alias is a one-line forwarder. Optimized to a tail-call by the
backend.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Inherits semantics from the delegated function.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_enqueue" takes dq as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc deque_push_back with dq, value
End Process

@Reasoning
Forwarder for queue API parity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Forwards to deque_pop_front.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Time: O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Inherits semantics.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "deque_dequeue" takes dq as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc deque_pop_front with dq
End Process
